ysis. Ruthless Democracy extends the cultural and geographical boundaries of the American Renaissance beyond the northeast to Indian Territory, Alta California, and the transnational sphere that Powell calls the American Diaspora. Arguing for the inclusion of new works, Powell envisions the canon of the American Renaissance as a fluid dialogue of disparate cultural voices.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aAmerican literaturexMinority authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aCultural pluralism in literature. 0aDemocracy in literature. 0aEthnic groups in literature. 0aEthnicity in literature. 0aLiterature and societyzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aMinorities in literature. 0aMinoritieszUnited StatesxIntellectual life. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh  aAbolition.  aAesthetics.  aAmerican: colonization.  aAnthropology.  aBeaver, Harold.  aBercovitch, Sacvan.  aBrown, Charles.  aCalhoun, John C.  aCapitalism.  aCherokee Phoenix.  aCherokee.  aColonization.  aCultural Studies.  aDemocracy.  aDigger Indians.  aDisability.  aDoctrine of Discovery.  aDomesticity.  aEconomy.  aFeminism.  aForgetting.  aFree Soil Movement.  aGarrison, William Lloyd.  aGleiter, Karin.  aHermeneutics.  aHybridity.  aIdeology.  aIndian Removal Act.  aIndustrial Revolution.  aJarvis, Edward.  aJefferson, Thomas.  aKinshasa, Kwando Μ.  aKnow-Nothings.  aLeslie, Joshua.  aLubiano, Wahneema.  aMasculinity.  aMexican-American War.  aMinstrelsy.  aMiscegenation.  aMonoculturalism.  aNationalism.  aNativism.  aNaumkeag Indians.  aOwens, Louis.  aPhilosophy.  aPostnationalism.  aQueerness.  aRadical democracy.  aRoberts, Joseph Jenkins.  aRuthless democracy.